      "\t\n",
      "\t\n",
      "\tCr addition improves oxidation resistance in Co-Al-W based superalloys primarily by acting as a reactive element that enhances oxide scale adherence at the metal/oxide interface [1]. While small Cr additions cannot form a continuous Cr₂O₃ scale, they modify the oxide composition and improve interfacial bonding compared to the base Co-9Al-9W alloy [2]. Cr also reduces oxide scale thickness, though less effectively than Si additions [1]. For adequate oxidation protection through Cr₂O₃ formation, high Cr levels are necessary [2]. However, excessive Cr additions induce brittle secondary phases and reduce γ' solvus temperature and stability, requiring balanced alloying with γ'-stabilizing elements (Ni, Ta, W) to maintain microstructural integrity [2]. The optimal Cr addition should promote protective Al₂O₃ or Cr₂O₃ scale formation without compromising the bulk microstructure [2].\n",
